Introduction

The purpose of this research is to look into fantasy football related data. We will begin by reading in some yearly fantasy football data from 2019, 2018, 2014, and 2009. All of this data is calculated on a points-per-reception basis, which means that players received one point for every ball caughtthis increases the value of receivers. Players also receive points for yards gained and for touchdowns. The scoring method is consistent throughout all of the datasets. We will look at the relationship between different fantasy football points and different variables for different positions. For example, for quarterbacks, we will look at the relationship between interceptions and fantasy points. For running backs, we will look at the relationship between running touchdowns and fantasy points. We will see how the median points per game for different positions has changed over the past 10 years. These are just a few of the questions we will be answering throughout this EDA.
Overall, the goal of this EDA is to become more familiar with the fantasy football data and explore different relationships between variables. Ultimately, we hope to offer conclusions on our findings that will prove to be useful to fantasy owners. Some of the newly discovered relationships between variables may be very helpful for fantasy owners when they are selecting their team.

Reading in the Datasets / Tidying

After loading in the packages, we read in the fantasy football data.

library(janitor)
library(corrplot)
library(tidyverse)
ff_data_2019 <- read_csv(file = "data/unprocessed/yearly/2019.csv") %>% 
  clean_names() 

ff_data_2018 <- read_csv(file = "data/unprocessed/yearly/2018.csv") %>% 
               clean_names()

ff_data_2014 <- read_csv(file = "data/unprocessed/yearly/2014.csv") %>% 
  clean_names()

ff_data_2009 <- read_csv(file = "data/unprocessed/yearly/2009.csv") %>% 
  clean_names()


All of these datasets are from yearly fantasy football datasets from Fantasy Football Data Pros. Originally, when I imported each file into R (one file per year2019, 2018, 2014, and 2009), there were many duplicate columns, and the names of the columns were ambiguous. Hence, I needed to eliminate duplicate columns and rename the existing columns to become more clear and descriptive. For most of the yearly datasets, I filtered such that the players represented needed to have above a certain threshold of fantasy points (30). This is because I wanted my visualizations to depict players who get considerable playing time. If a player is getting below 30 points on the season, they barely are in the game and their statistics may be influenced by the low playing time sample size. For example, they might have one target and one catch on the year, which would give a reception rate of 100%. However, this is misleading since the player was only thrown one ball over the entire year.


Missingness in the data was not an issue. All of the observations had values in each row, even if that value was just zero. If the player was a free agent or did not get any playing time, the position was set to zero (which is somewhat nonsensical), but I was able to filter this out in my datasets.


Additionally, for many of the datasets, I added new columns that would give meaningful information. I will explain the new columns (reception rate, completion rate, points per game) I added: Reception rate is equal to receptions over targets. Completion rate is equal to completions over attempts. And points per game is just the total fantasy points over the season divided by the number of games played. Check the code below as an example if you are interested to see how this was done. The code also shows how I selected columns specifically so no duplicates appeared.

tidy_ff_data_2019 <- ff_data_2019 %>% 
  #make new column
  mutate(
    rec_rate = (rec /tgt)
  ) %>% 
  #make new column
  mutate(
    comp_rate = (cmp / att_9)
  ) %>%
  #make new column
  mutate(
    ppg = (fantasy_points / g)
  ) %>% 
  #clearer name
  rename(
    att = att_9
  ) %>% 
  #do not want repetitive columns
  select(-yds_10, -att_12, -yds_13, -passing_att, 
         -yds_16, -x1)


For the ff_by_pos_xxxx datasets, I grouped by position and found the median points per game for that position. See code below for example.

ff_by_pos_2019 <- tidy_ff_data_2019 %>% 
  #remove position = 0
  #want players with good playign times, so filter by fantasy points
  filter(pos != 0 & fantasy_points > 30) %>%
  group_by(pos) %>% 
  #new column 
  summarise(
    med_ppg_by_pos_2019 = median(fantasy_points / g)
  )

For the ff_over_time datset, I created a new dataset so that I could track how the median points per game for different positions changed over time. Each row represents a position and year combination. With this dataset, we can see the median points per game for each position and year combination and compare. I had to merge different datasets from different years, and then use pivot_longer() so that the year and ppg would become their own columns. See code for example.

#join fantasy football datasets
joined_ff <- left_join(ff_by_pos_2019, ff_by_pos_2014, by = "pos")

ff_over_time <- joined_ff %>% left_join(ff_by_pos_2009, by = "pos") %>% 
  #rename columns
  rename(
    "2019" = med_ppg_by_pos_2019,
    "2014" = med_ppg_by_pos_2014,
    "2009" = med_ppg_by_pos_2009
  ) %>% 
  #expand 
  pivot_longer(c('2019', '2014', '2009'), names_to = "year", values_to = "ppg")

For a more in-depth analysis of the process or to clearly see the steps, you can visit the data_cleaning.R script. We will now read in and store the tidied data sets below.

Exploration / Body

Investigating Distributions (Univariate)

We just want to get familiar with the fantasy_points variable. We are going to be working with it a lot, so lets see its distribution. Also, lets look at the distribution of ages of the players. Since there is only one variable in these plots, they would be considered univariate.

#distribution of fantasy points
ggplot(tidy_ff_data_2019, aes(x = fantasy_points)) +
  geom_density() +
  #labeling
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Fantasy Points",
    x = "Fantasy Points"
  )

ggplot(tidy_ff_data_2019, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 22) +
  #labeling
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Ages of Players",
    x = "Age"
  )


We see that fantasy points are spread across a large amount of values. Most players have fantasy points between 0-100, but there are some players who have points past 300. There appears to a right skew.
It looks like most of the players are around 25 years of age. There are not too many players in their 30s. There seem to be a few outliers who are players in their 40s. One of those outliers is certainly Tom Brady, the invincible quarterback. Again, there is a right skew.


Next, we will look at the positions and number of players of each position represented in this data.

tidy_ff_data_2019 %>% 
  #remove position = 0
  filter(pos != 0) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  #barplot
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = pos)) +
  #labeling
  labs(
    title = "Number of Players of Each Position",
    x = "Position"
  )


Most of the players represented are wide receivers, followed by running backs, followed by tide ends and then quarterbacks. This makes sense, since in a standard formation, there are multiple wide receivers on the field at one time. The same cannot be said for quarterback, running backs, or tide ends. Quarterbacks rarely get injured compared to other positions, so it would make sense that there are less quarterbacks on rosters and less quarterbacks represented in this data.


Exploring Relationships (Mostly Bivarate + Multivariate)

Next, lets look at how points differ based on position. We will look at two years below: 2018 and 2019. I have decided to focus on these years because they are the most recent and most related to the current NFL in 2021 (the 2020 NFL season was an anomaly due to COVID-19, so it will not be analyzed). Since there are two variables in the plots (position and points), they are considered bivariate.

ff_by_pos_2019 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = pos, y = med_ppg_by_pos_2019)) +
  #barplot
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Median Points Per Game for Different Positions in 2019",
    x = "Position",
    y = "Median Points per Game"
  )

ff_by_pos_2018 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = pos, y = med_ppg_by_pos_2018)) +
  #barplot
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Median Points Per game for Different Positions in 2018",
    x = "Position",
    y = "Median Points per Game"
  )


In these two years, it looks like we see the same approximate trends. They are unimodal, with quarterbacks scoring the most points on average. Then we have running backs, then wide receivers, then tide ends. Obviously, in real life each position contributes to the game in different, necessary ways. However, in fantasy football, the quarterback seems to be the most productive position. This is interesting, and we should now look at if this was always the case. Have quarterbacks become more productive over time? Lets take a look below. Also, since there are three variables, this would be considered multivariate analysis.


ff_over_time %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(year, ppg)) +
  #group by position
    geom_line(aes(group = pos), color = "grey50") +
  #distinguish positions by color 
    geom_point(aes(color = pos)) +
  labs(
    title = "Median Points Per game for Different Positions Over a 10 Year Span",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Median Points per Game"
  )


This is a very interesting graphic that lets us see trends over a ten year period. Since there are three variables, this is multivariate analysis. We see that the gap in scoring between the quarterback and other positions has increased significantly from 2009 to 2014. Both QBs (quarterbacks) and TEs (tide ends) saw point point increases from 2009 to 2014, and then from 2014 to 2019. However, the RBs (running backs) saw points decrease from 2009 to 2014, but then increase from 2014 to 2019. We see the exact opposite trend for WRs (wide receivers). Overall, football teams have been throwing the ball a lot more. Hence, it makes sense that quarterbacks would be putting up more points. Additionally, lots of these passes are short and going to running backs. This might explain why WRs see a decrease in points but RBs see an increase in points from 2014-2019.


Now, lets dive into one year of fantasy data (2019) and see which variables are really correlated with the points. Again, we are doing 2019 because it is most recent and consequently most representative of the 2021 season. The 2020 season was an anomaly due to many unique COVID rules. Lets start with wide receivers and look at the relationship between fantasy points and receiving yards.

tidy_ff_data_2019 %>% 
  filter(pos == "WR") %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = receiving_yds, y = fantasy_points)) +
  geom_point() +
  #smoothed conditional mean 
  geom_smooth() +
  labs(
    title = "Fantasy Points vs. Receiving Yards for Wide Receivers",
    x = "Receiving Yards",
    y = "Fantasy Points"
  )


This looks to be a very strong positive relationship, as we can clearly draw a positively sloped line that runs closely through the data points. Hence, receiving yards is very correlated to fantasy points, which is what we would expect considering receivers are rewarded points for each yard caught. What about reception rate? We should facet based on position, since each position generally has a different type of throw thrown at them.

tidy_ff_data_2019 %>% 
  #using overall dataset because want many positions
  #want players with a good amount of receptions
  filter(rec >= 20) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = rec_rate, y = fantasy_points)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = loess) +
  #different cells for different positions
  facet_wrap(~pos) +
  labs(
    title = "Fantasy Points vs. Reception Rate for Different Positions",
    x = "Reception Rate",
    y = "Fantasy Points"
  )


This is pretty interesting. The first thing I notice is that WRs have a lower average reception rate than both RBs and TEs. Most of the points on the plot for WRs are between .5 and .7 on the x-axis of rec_rate. Most of the points on the plot for RBs are between .7 and .9 of rec_rate. And most of the points on the plot for TEs are between a wider range of .55 and .85 of rec_rate. This all makes sense, since running backs catch a lot of short-yardage screens, which are easier to catch since there is low coverage and a quick, short pass. Wide receivers generally catch farther balls, where there is more coverage and they have a lower probability of catching since it is a farther distance. Tide ends do a mix of short and long passes, which explains why its data trends are in-between those of the WRs and RBs.
For running backs and tide ends, there seems to be low correlation between reception rate and fantasy points. There doesnt seems to be a clear trend in points based on the lines. For wide receivers, there does seem to be a stronger positive correlation between reception rate and fantasy points. This might be because wide receivers catch balls from farther throws, so a higher success rate could translate to a lot more points. For example, if running backs are just given 1-yard throws, reception rate wouldnt really matter since each throw on average would only give the running back a few points. But if wide receivers are given 30-yards throws, reception rate might matter since more catches would mean lots more points.


This is interesting. I bet there is a closer relationship between fantasy points and targets. Let us check below.


To review, a target is whenever a player is thrown the ball. It counts as a target whether the player catches the ball or not. A reception is when the ball is actually caught.


tidy_ff_data_2019 %>% 
  filter(rec >= 20) %>% 
  #want players with a good amount of receptions (get good playing time)
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = tgt, y = fantasy_points)) +
  geom_point() +
  #smoothed conditional mean
  geom_smooth() +
  #distinguish by position
  facet_wrap(~pos) +
  labs(
    title = "Fantasy Points vs. Targets for Different Positions",
    x = "Targets",
    y = "Fantasy Points"
  )


Yes, it looks like I was right. Across all positions, we see a clear positive relationship between targets and fantasy points. This makes sense, since more targets means more opportunities to score points. Lets now look closer at running backs.

tidy_ff_data_2019 %>% 
  #filter by running backs
  filter(pos == "RB") %>%

As expected there is a clear relationship between running yards and fantasy points. There is a positive relationship between the variables. As running yards increases, fantasy points increases. The positive line that runs closely throught he points shows this as well. Lets now look at quarterbacks. We would expect to see a positive relationship between passing yards and fantasy points.

tidy_ff_data_2019_qb %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = passing_yds, y = fantasy_points)) +

Again, we see what we would expect. More passing yards correlates to more fantasy points. This is a positive, nearly linear relationship. Lets now look at how the points are related to completion rate. Based on what we see saw for RBs and WRs, I would expect this to be a pretty low correlation. We would expect volume to be more important.

#completion rate isn't in our qb subset, so use overall dataset
tidy_ff_data_2019 %>%

As expected, there isnt a clear correlation between completion rate of throws and fantasy points. If a quarterback converts all their throws but only tries for 1-yard throws, this would mean a high completion rate with low fantasy points. Some quarterbacks do only try for short passes, so this shows why the correlation is apparently low. What we do see is that most of the points on the plot are within .6 and .7 on the x-axis, so this is probably where the average completion rate for quarterbacks in the NFL lies (60-70%). Now lets looks at volume through pass attempts vs.fantasy points.

We see a positive, nearly linear relationship between pass attempts and fantasy points. This makes sense since every pass is an opportunity to score points. Based on the data trends we have been seeing, I would rather have a high-volume quarterback with a low completion percentage than a low-volume quarterback with a high completion percentage. This data is interesting though, because the top QB scorer only has about 400 attempts, which seems to be about average. How can this be? Well, anyone familiar with football knows that this outlier is Lamar Jacksonhe is a quarterback who likes to run way more than other quarterbacks. This explains how he gets so many points without throwing that often. In fantasy scoring, running yards are worth more points than throwing yards, so it makes sense how Lamar Jackson is able to rack up so many fantasy points. Exploring Correlations (Multivariate)

Now, as we prepare to conclude our EDA, lets look at correlations between different statistics for QBs. This will give us a better understanding of how different variables are related to overall fantasy points.

corr_qb = cor(tidy_ff_data_2019_qb)
corrplot(corr_qb, method = "number", title = "Correlation Between Different Statistics and Fantasy Points for QBs",
         #margins so title appears cleanly
         mar=c(0, 0, 2, 0))


This is a really interesting graphic that gives a lot of information. To begin, we see that the variable that is most closely related to fantasy points in passing touchdowns, not passing yards. This does make sense based on how fantasy points are calculated. 25 passing yards are equal to one point, while a touchdown thrown is equal to 4 points. Hence, 100 passing yards is equal to one touchdown thrown, and it seems as though touchdowns may be easier to come by compared to lots of yards. We see that interceptions are the least correlated with fantasy points. While the relationship is still positive, it is not that strong (.56). Attempts and completions also show high positive correlation with fantasy points, which is what we would expect. Interceptions is actually most correlated with attempts, which does make sense. More throws equals more chances to throw interceptions.

Now, let us look at the correlations between variables for WRs.

corr_wr = cor(tidy_ff_data_2019_wr)

corrplot(corr_wr, method = "number", title = "Correlation Between Different Statistics and Fantasy Points for WRs",
         #margins so title appears cleanly
         mar=c(0, 0, 2, 0))


The first thing that jumps out is the extremely low correlation between rec_rate and all of the other variables represented. Fantasy points are barely correlated with reception rate at a value of .22. The highest correlation with fantasy points is receiving yards, at a whopping value of .98. Surprisingly, receiving touchdowns only has a correlation with fantasy points of .81. Wide receivers are rewarded 1 point for 10 receiving yards and 6 points per receiving touchdown. Hence, one touchdown is equal to 60 receiving yards. For wide receivers, receiving yards are more important than the touchdowns. Maybe touchdowns are more difficult for receivers than quarterbacks? Lets see.


First lets look at mean passing touchdowns for quarterbacks (dataset was filtered such that quarterbacks in the sample have lots of completions):

mean(tidy_ff_data_2019_qb$passing_td)
## [1] 15.45098


Now lets look at mean receiving touchdowns for wide receivers (dataset was filtered such that receivers in the sample have lots of targets and receptions):

mean(tidy_ff_data_2019_wr$receiving_td)
## [1] 4.037383


Yes, it looks like the mean receiving touchdowns of receivers is about 4, while the mean passing touchdown for quarterbacks is close to 15.5. Hence, quarterbacks on average throw more than three times the amount of touchdowns that receivers catch. This is probably due to the fact that quarterbacks can throw touchdown to both tide ends and running backs as well. This all helps explain why quarterbacks exhibit a higher linear correlation between fantasy points and passing touchdowns compared to the correlation between fantasy points and receiving touchdowns for wide receivers.

Conclusions

Overall, after conducting this EDA, we now have a much more thorough understanding of the relationships between different football statistics and fantasy points. We have seen that fantasy points display (mostly) linear, positive relationships with receiving yards, targets, rushing yards, passing yards, interceptions, and passing attempts. Basically, when players are given more opportunities to score in the form of targets or passing attempts, they are given an increased chance to score fantasy points through yards and touchdowns. The relationship between all of the aforementioned variables does make sense in the context of football. It was interesting to see that for passing attempts, Lamar Jackson was able to finish as top scorer without having a high number of attempts because of his rushing ability. Hence, different players are able to garner points in different ways, sometimes in ways that are unconventional for their position (such as running as a quarterback). We saw that some statistics, such as completion rate and reception rate, are less correlated to fantasy points. This is likely because a high reception or completion rate does not imply high volume. If a player catches all of his passes, but is thrown a low number of passes, then the player is not a top fantasy scorer. Hence, we conclude that volume is more important than efficiency in the context of fantasy football. Finally, we saw that passing touchdowns are extremely correlated (positively) with fantasy points for quarterbacks, while rushing touchdowns are less correlated (while still positively) with fantasy points for running backs. We then saw that quarterbacks on average throw more touchdowns than running backs run forthis may indicate that quarterback receive more of their points from touchdowns, and hence touchdowns is a better predictor of fantasy points for quarterbacks.
